02s\\n\\nOK\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-002_Make_raw_geometry_ingestion_cache-aware_resumable_and_provenance-rich/stdout.jsonl:119:{\"type\":\"item.updated\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_26\",\"type\":\"todo_list\",\"items\":[{\"text\":\"Extend geometry fetch library for cache validation, refetch controls, and per-asset provenance\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Wire CLI/config controls and manifest records through scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Add regression tests for cache reuse, refetch, corrupted cache, and skeleton failure\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Run requested verification commands and summarize results\",\"completed\":true}]}}\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-002_Make_raw_geometry_ingestion_cache-aware_resumable_and_provenance-rich/stdout.jsonl:120:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_71\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Implemented FW-M5-002 end-to-end.\\n\\nThe raw fetch path in [mesh_pipeline.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/mesh_pipeline.py#L104) is now cache-aware and resumable: it validates cached `.ply` and `.swc` files, treats zero-byte/malformed cache entries as invalid, writes fetched assets atomically, supports forced refetch and optional skeleton hard-fail mode, and records structured per-asset provenance with `fetch_status` values like `cache_hit`, `fetched`, `skipped`, and `failed`. The manifest contract in [geometry_contract.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/src/flywire_wave/geometry_contract.py#L111) now stores that `raw_asset_provenance` and can load/merge existing records so rerunning fetches or later processed-asset builds does not clobber prior state.\\n\\nThe CLI in [02_fetch_meshes.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py#L36) now accepts `--refetch-meshes`, `--refetch-skeletons`, and `--require-skeletons`, writes per-root provenance into the manifest, reports aggregate cache-hit/fetch/failure counts, and preserves existing bundle records on reruns. [03_build_wave_assets.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/scripts/03_build_wave_assets.py#L64) now preserves the raw-fetch provenance when processed assets are built. I also added regression coverage in [tests/test_mesh_pipeline_fetch.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_mesh_pipeline_fetch.py#L44), plus manifest/integration assertions in [tests/test_geometry_contract.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_geometry_contract.py#L52) and [tests/test_config_paths.py](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/tests/test_config_paths.py#L72). Config examples were updated with the new knobs in [config/local.yaml](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/config/local.yaml) and [config/visual_subset.example.yaml](/home/jack/Documents/github/personal/fly_neural_simulation/flywire_wave_repo/config/visual_subset.example.yaml).\\n\\nVerified with `make test` and `.venv/bin/python -m unittest tests.test_mesh_pipeline_fetch -v`. Both passed.\"}}\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-002_Make_raw_geometry_ingestion_cache-aware_resumable_and_provenance-rich/stdout.jsonl:121:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_26\",\"type\":\"todo_list\",\"items\":[{\"text\":\"Extend geometry fetch library for cache validation, refetch controls, and per-asset provenance\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Wire CLI/config controls and manifest records through scripts/02_fetch_meshes.py\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Add regression tests for cache reuse, refetch, corrupted cache, and skeleton failure\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Run requested verification commands and summarize results\",\"completed\":true}]}}\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:19:  operational_claim: \"In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\"\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:29:  baseline_definitions:\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:30:    P0: Canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same connectome slice and readout.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:31:    P1: Stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:40:    - id: m1_survives_stronger_baseline\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:41:      statement: Survival against the stronger reduced baseline P1.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:56:    comparison: surface_wave/intact versus matched baseline/intact, with the intact-minus-baseline gap contrasted against the shuffled condition\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:57:    expected_relationship: The surface-wave model produces a small but reproducible shared-output departure relative to the matched baseline.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:75:    comparison: surface_wave/intact versus matched baseline/intact, then intact versus shuffled\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:96:    comparison: (surface_wave/intact - baseline/intact) versus (surface_wave/shuffled - baseline/shuffled)\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:101:      - matched baseline arm\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:105:  - id: m1_survives_stronger_baseline\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:106:    name: Survival against stronger reduced baseline P1\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:107:    description: Confirm that the shared-output effect is not explained away by a stronger reduced baseline with explicit integration current or delay structure.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:115:    comparison: surface_wave/intact versus baseline P1/intact, with the same comparison available under shuffled topology\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:118:      - baseline P1 arm\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:122:    notes: No numeric margin is locked yet; only the requirement that the effect survive the stronger reduced baseline.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:150:      description: Show point baseline and surface-wave model side by side on the same T4/T5-centered circuit.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:166:  - id: surface_vs_baseline_split_view\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:168:    description: Side-by-side view of scalar baseline activity and distributed surface state for the same circuit and stimulus.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:169:    artifact_name: ui/surface_vs_baseline_split_view.json\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:172:    description: Overlay of shared output traces for the matched surface-wave and baseline conditions.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:186:  - id: baseline_challenge_comparison\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:188:    description: P0 versus P1 baseline challenge plot for the same observable family.\n./config/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:189:    artifact_name: plots/baseline_challenge_comparison.png\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:104:- At least one nontrivial anisotropic fixture case is covered by regression tests, along with boundary-handling behavior that demonstrates the implemented semantics are real rather than metadata-only.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:118:- Area: validation / visualization / developer tooling\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:121:Milestone 6 is only complete if the team can initialize a pulse on one neuron, verify that surface propagation behaves stably enough for later engine work, compare coarse and fine operators quantitatively, and inspect the results without digging through raw arrays. Right now there is no standard harness that exercises those numerical behaviors, no operator quality report, and no offline visualization flow for reviewing what the assembled operators are actually doing on the mesh.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:124:Add a Milestone 6 validation and inspection workflow that consumes local operator bundles and produces actionable diagnostics. The workflow should initialize localized test fields, run a lightweight stability-oriented evolution or repeated operator application suitable for pre-engine validation, compute operator quality metrics, and generate an offline report that overlays relevant outputs on the mesh and patch decomposition. The goal is not to build the final wave engine; it is to make operator quality, pulse localization, and coarse-versus-fine behavior inspectable and regression-testable before Milestone 10 begins.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:127:- A documented local command or script can generate an operator QA report for fixture assets or previously built neuron bundles without requiring FlyWire access.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:128:- The report includes at least pulse initialization, boundary-mask inspection, coarse-versus-fine projection or reconstruction views, and a compact summary of operator quality metrics with pass, warn, or fail semantics.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:130:- At least one smoke-style automated test generates the report from fixture assets and asserts the expected output files and summary fields.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:135:- A smoke-style fixture run that produces an operator QA report and asserts the summary fields plus deterministic output paths\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:140:## FW-M6-006 - Run a Milestone 6 implementation verification pass and publish a readiness report\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:147:Even if the Milestone 6 build tickets land individually, the repo still needs one explicit follow-up pass that verifies the pieces work together as a coherent operator pipeline. Without a dedicated implementation-verification ticket, it is too easy to stop at local success on isolated subtasks while leaving behind contract drift, missing docs, broken report paths, weak regression coverage, or untested assumptions between fine operators, coarse operators, transfer maps, and QA tooling.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:150:Perform a senior-level verification pass over the completed Milestone 6 implementation and publish a concise readiness report in-repo. This pass should exercise the full operator pipeline on fixture assets and at least one realistic local bundle, confirm that documentation matches the shipped behavior, identify any mismatches or scientific risks, and either close them directly or record them as follow-on issues. Treat this as an integration and audit ticket rather than a net-new feature ticket.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:153:- The full Milestone 6 workflow is executed end-to-end using the shipped commands and local assets, with results captured in a deterministic report location.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:154:- The verification pass checks contract compatibility across geometry assets, fine operators, coarse operators, transfer operators, boundary handling, anisotropy settings, and QA report generation.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:155:- The readiness report summarizes what was verified, what remains risky or deferred, and whether Milestone 6 is ready to support Milestone 10 engine work.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:176:report path, but the cached local mesh bundle currently covers only\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:191:  report records the refreshed bundle composition.\n./agent_tickets/milestone_6_surface_discretization_tickets.md:200:the generated `milestone_6_readiness.md`; the report currently shows 0 cached\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:33:To test that, we did not just build a solver. We built the full experimental scaffold around it. We locked the scientific claim, defined a biologically defensible fruit fly visual subcircuit, created reproducible data registries and subset selection tools, converted neuron morphology into wave-ready geometry and operators, built the baseline simulator for fair comparison, and then integrated the first working surface-wave simulation path on top of that.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:35:What makes this valid is that the system is structured as an actual falsifiable experiment. The same circuit and same stimulus can be run through both a conventional baseline model and our surface-wave model, with shared readouts and milestone-specific readiness checks. So even though we did not finish the full end-to-end scientific proof, we *did* build the framework needed to test the idea rigorously.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:60:Math/physics-heavy = model formulation, numerical operators, stability, wave equations, discretization choices, validation metrics, analysis design\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:73:Grant owns the wave model, discretization choices, coupling assumptions, stability reasoning, and validation logic\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:103:design validation metrics\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:113:interpret baseline vs wave differences\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:129:In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:137:a shared downstream readout so comparison to baselines stays fair\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:143:a decoder or readout unavailable to the baselines\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:147:P0: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:148:P1: stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:152: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:153:What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:156: A geometry-sensitive shared-output effect, preferably on null-direction suppression or response latency, that survives a stronger reduced baseline.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:166:##### Evidence ladder\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:170:Very strong: the effect survives the stronger reduced baseline P1\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:174:10–25 s: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:181:split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:186:P0 versus P1 challenge-baseline comparison plot\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:219:P0 and P1 baseline definitions are explicit\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:230:survival against a stronger reduced baseline\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:294:summary reports and previews for the locked subnetwork\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:335:manifest validation\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:371:exporting manifests and reports\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:576:#### Milestone 9 — Build the baseline non-wave simulator\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:586:baseline\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:598:defining a fair baseline model\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:599:making sure the baseline is not a strawman\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:603:the same experiment manifest runs in baseline mode\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:714:baseline vs wave comparisons are quantitative, not just visual\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:716:#### Milestone 13 — Build the validation ladder\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:746:reproducible differences between baseline and wave mode\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:751:regression scripts\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:752:notebooks / reports\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:756:defining the actual validation criteria\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:761:each validation layer has automated tests or notebooks\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:763:model changes can be regression-checked\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:784:baseline vs wave comparison mode\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:855:compare baseline and wave mode\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:978:same experiment runs in both baseline and wave mode\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:993:validation logic\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1006:one baseline simulator\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1055:validation metrics\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1080:designing the validation ladder\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1100:Milestone 13\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1209:- each subset emits a manifest, stats report, and preview image,\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1328:Before the wave version becomes the star, build a boring baseline.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1330:This baseline should use:\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1341:- any experiment can run in `baseline` or `surface_wave` mode,\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1415:- your UI can compare outputs between baseline and wave mode,\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1418:### Milestone 13 — Validation ladder\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1445:- validation results are part of CI or at least scripted regression runs.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1473:- compare baseline vs wave mode,\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1516:- compare to baseline,\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1555:7. build baseline non-wave simulator  \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1573:- baseline vs surface-wave comparison\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1590:> **In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1594:This is the safer scientific frame because strong fly visual baselines already do a lot with simple neurons. A recent connectome-constrained visual-system model recovered ON/OFF segregation and T4/T5 direction selectivity using passive leaky linear non-spiking neurons with single electrical compartments for most cells, and an earlier T4 model reported that moving all synaptic inputs to the dendrite base left the simulated responses nearly unchanged. More broadly, effective point-neuron models can capture rich dendritic computations when given stronger synaptic integration terms, so the baseline challenge has to be real. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07939-3))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1600:## 1) What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1619:- **Shared output readout.** Downstream circuitry still sees an ordinary scalar or low-dimensional readout, so comparison with the baseline is fair.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1629:- no hand-fitted per-synapse delays in the wave model that the baseline is denied\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1642:### Best baselines\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1644:Use **two** baselines.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1646:**P0: canonical point baseline**  \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1647:Passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons, matched to the connectome and readout. That is the strongest “standard” baseline because it already works well in the fly visual system. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07939-3))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1649:**P1: stronger challenge baseline**  \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1679:Meaning: a measurable difference between wave and baseline on a readout both models share, where that difference depends on intact morphology or synapse topology and is challengeable by stronger reduced baselines.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1699:\\big(M_{\\text{surface,intact}} - M_{\\text{baseline,intact}}\\big)\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1701:\\big(M_{\\text{surface,shuffled}} - M_{\\text{baseline,shuffled}}\\big)\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1708:- **detectability**: wave and baseline differ on a shared readout\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1712:### Evidence ladder\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1724:The effect survives the stronger reduced baseline P1 as well.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1743:- an effect that disappears once the baseline gets explicit delays\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1749:> **The surface model matters if it produces a small, reproducible, geometry-dependent change on a shared readout, ideally null-direction suppression or latency, and that change survives a stronger reduced baseline.**\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1771:left = matched point baseline  \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1774:The baseline shows scalar membrane activity. The surface model shows distributed state evolving on the dendrite.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1789:- surface versus baseline\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1812:T4/T5 is the best first demo substrate because they are the first direction-selective neurons in the fly visual pathway, their computation is explicitly dendritic, anatomy predicts tuning, and strong simple baselines already exist. That makes any surviving small effect much more credible. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8371135/))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1827:3. **Survival against a stronger reduced baseline**\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1838:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1842:A **geometry-sensitive shared-output effect**, preferably on **null-direction suppression or response latency**, that survives a stronger reduced baseline.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1859:- Put morphology-resolved dynamics only where morphology is mechanistically implicated **and** strong simple baselines already pose a real challenge: that means T4/T5, not lamina, not whole-brain feedback. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-017-0046-4))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1916:- **Main engineering risk:** even this case still demands accurate synapse-to-dendrite localization and a fair stronger baseline.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1952:It is the smallest boundary I would actually sign off on for Milestone 2. The minimal T4a-only circuit is enough to debug the wave engine, but it leaves you too exposed to the criticism that any geometry-sensitive effect is peculiar to one polarity channel. The balanced choice adds only the matched OFF sister pathway, keeps the active field local, keeps the readout at T4/T5 rather than in wide-field tangential circuitry, and gives you a built-in replication across contrast polarity without importing LPi/LPTC-scale complications. It also respects the strongest baseline challenge: simple single-compartment and connectome-constrained models already do a lot in this system, so the first win has to come from a clean local morphology test, not from extra downstream machinery. Concretely, I would lock the first vertical slice to **T4a/T5a + direct ON/OFF reduced inputs + central patch + terminal readout**, driven by bright and dark moving edges or apparent-motion bar pairs along the chosen horizontal axis, with **geometry-sensitive null-direction suppression** as the primary metric and **response latency** as the mechanistic companion. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-017-0046-4))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2016:- **Strong baseline danger: T4 may simply be too well explained by simple models for some stimuli.** Multi-compartment vs single-compartment differences can be very small for moving bars, and modern connectome-constrained models already recover key T4/T5 properties with simple neuron dynamics. If your effect survives only against a weak baseline, the boundary is not the win. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41593-017-0046-4))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2093:For Milestones 11, 12, and 13, your own roadmap already frames them as **hybrid morphology classes**, **readouts/task layer**, and **validation ladder**, and the repo’s readiness pass already points at the downstream workstreams as **mixed_fidelity**, **metrics**, and **validation**. So the fastest path is to build directly on the current solver/execution stack, not start a new architecture.  \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2225:This is Milestone 13 work that pays for itself instantly.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2251:- **point** roots: existing baseline/P1 path\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2253:The repo already has the surface solver, coupled execution path, and a baseline comparison workflow, so this is mostly an interface problem, not a physics rewrite.   \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2265:That is enough to compare baseline vs wave and enough to support the existing result-bundle/readiness flow. \n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2267:#### Milestone 13: validation\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2274:That is the minimum serious validation ladder.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2314:        r: make_point_solver(r, manifest.baseline_model)\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2338:    validator = init_validation_state(roots)\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2448:        \"validation\": finalize_validation(runtime.validator),\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2455:1. **Add operator-sign validation**\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2460:6. **Implement Milestone 13 validators**\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-002_Make_raw_geometry_ingestion_cache-aware_resumable_and_provenance-rich/prompt.md:7:Make the code changes, run the relevant tests or validation commands, and finish with a concise summary of what changed and what you verified.\n./agent_tickets/runs/20260321T170513Z/FW-M5-002_Make_raw_geometry_ingestion_cache-aware_resumable_and_provenance-rich/prompt.md:16:- Re-running the fetch step against already downloaded valid assets reports ca